## 2. Enrollment Attrition Analysis

Confusion regarding termination numbers (85,000 vs. 120,000 vs. 160,000+) is resolved by analyzing the federal **grace period mandate** (45 C.F.R. § 156.270). Enrollees receiving advance premium tax credits are entitled to a three-month grace period before termination for non-payment.

| Timeline | Event | Cumulative Terminations | Context |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Jan 31, 2026** | Close of Open Enrollment | **85,000** | Immediate non-renewals and failures to pay initial "binder" premiums. |
| **April 6, 2026** | Mid-Spring Reporting | **~120,000** | First wave of grace periods expiring for January/February non-payment. |
| **June 1, 2026** | Current Status | **160,000+** | Full realization of grace period expirations and mid-year dropouts. |
| **June 1, 2026** | Active Enrollment | **443,024** | Net effectuated enrollment remaining in the market. |

**Demographic Impact:**
*   **Rural Flight:** 15 of the 20 counties with the steepest proportional coverage loss are rural.
*   **Plan Downgrading:** Bronze-tier enrollment increased by **30%** (approx. 33,000 enrollees) as consumers chased lower premiums, exposing them to an average deductible of **$7,186** (vs. $5,304 for Silver).

