## 3. Regional Disparities (Rating Areas 1–9)

While the statewide average hike is 21.5%, local market dynamics vary drastically.

| Rating Area | Region | Key Dynamics & Carrier Landscape |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Area 1** | Northwest (Erie) | Moderate competition (Highmark, UPMC, Geisinger). Network adequacy concerns outside Erie metro. |
| **Area 2** | North Central (Rural) | **Highest Vulnerability.** Thinnest carrier mix (Geisinger/Highmark). Longest drive times to specialists. |
| **Area 3** | Northeast (Poconos) | **Highest Price Dispersion.** Oscar (+23.1%) vs. Partners (-10.1%). Shopping is critical; autopilot renewal is financially dangerous. |
| **Area 4** | Southwest (Pittsburgh) | Dominated by vertically integrated systems (Highmark, UPMC). Tiered cost-sharing expanding; plan choice equals hospital network choice. |
| **Area 5** | West Central (Alleghenies) | Rural/mountainous. High reliance on Geisinger/UPMC/Highmark. Rising uncompensated care reported by local hospitals. |
| **Area 6** | Central / Lehigh Valley | **Active Network Disruption.** UnitedHealthcare vs. LVHN dispute displacing ~50k commercial and 5.4k Medicare Advantage members. |
| **Area 7** | South Central (York/Lancaster) | "Dutch Country" small-business hub. Site of PID’s primary "cliff" example (York County couple facing 408% hike). |
| **Area 8** | Philadelphia Metro | Most carrier-dense (IBX, QCC, Oscar, Ambetter, etc.). High volume of ancillary billing disputes (radiology, pathology). |
| **Area 9** | Capital Region (Harrisburg) | Home to Capital Blue Cross (+24.6%). Fulton and Juniata counties identified as critically carrier-thin. |

